  "exemplar_id": "ex_stimulant_acs_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "Middle-aged male bus driver presenting with 30 minutes of sudden-onset, dull, pressure-like left chest pain rated 7/10 that began while shovelling the driveway. He has known hypertension and hypercholesterolemia (on rosuvastatin and lisinopril), is a 20-year half-to-full pack-a-day smoker, and reports a temperature of 38°C and a sensation of racing heart. He denies alcohol and marijuana. The doctor has just learned the patient has used crystal methamphetamine for the past seven years.",
  "good_next_question": "When was the last time that you used crystal meth?",
  "rationale": "This question pins down the temporal relationship between stimulant exposure and the index event, which is the pivot point of the entire case. In a patient with classic exertional pressure-like chest pain and conventional risk factors, ACS is already high on the list — but methamphetamine use radically changes both the mechanism (coronary vasospasm, accelerated atherosclerosis, sympathetic surge, hyperthermia/tachycardia explaining the fever and palpitations) and management (avoid beta-blockers as monotherapy, consider benzodiazepines, lower threshold for younger MI). A 'within hours' answer makes acute sympathomimetic toxicity the unifying diagnosis; 'six days ago' (the actual answer) doesn't exclude meth-related coronary disease but shifts toward chronic injury rather than acute intoxication. This question beats simply documenting 'drug use: yes' because dosing recency is what changes the immediate plan.",
  "tags": [
    "chest_pain",
    "cardiac",
    "substance_use",
    "risk_factor_probe",
    "timeline",
    "acs",
    "stimulant_toxicity"
  ],
